  {
    "type": "theory",
    "title": "ðŸ“š Introducing Yourself",
    "content": {
      "introduction": "When introducing yourself in dholuo, it is expected that you reveal your name, your occupation, and to say a little bit about where you come from.",
      "phrases": [
        {
            "dholuo": "Nyingi nga?",
            "literal": "Your name + who?",
            "english": "What is your name?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Nyinga Atieno",
            "literal": "My name + Atieno.", 
            "english": "My name is Atieno.",
            "notes": "This is how to respond when greeted with 'oyaore'. The word 'ahinya' means 'a lot' or 'verily'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Iluongani Atieno.",
            "literal": "You call me + Atieno", 
            "english": "You call me Atieno.",
            "notes": "This is another way of saying your name. The verb 'luongo' is 'to call'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Iluongoni ng'a?",
            "english": "What is your name?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Ia kanye?",
            "literal": "You come from + where?", 
            "english": "Where do you come from?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Aa Seme.",
            "english": "I come from Seme"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "An jaseme/An nyaseme",
            "literal": "I'm a man from Seme/I'm a daughter of Seme", 
            "english": "I come from Seme.",
            "notes": "It is common for Luos to introduce themselves based on the area that they come from."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "In wuod ng'a?",
            "literal": "You + the son of + who?", 
            "english": "Whose son are you?",
            "notes": "It's also common for luos to introduce themselves based on who their parents or grandparents are. Tracing one's lineage was important to the social fabric."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "An wuod Adhiambo.",
            "literal": "I + the son of + Adhiambo",
            "english": "I'm the son of Adhiambo"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "In nyar ng'a?",
            "literal": "You + the daughter of + who?", 
            "english": "Whose daughter are you?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "An nyar Opiyo",
            "literal": "I + the daughter of + Opiyo", 
            "english": "I'm the daughter of Opiyo",
            "notes": "This greeting can be used at any time of day. The word 'dhi' means 'to go'."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "In nyakwar ng'a?",
            "literal": "You + the grandchild of + who?", 
            "english": "Whose grandchild are you?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "An nyakwar Odongo",
            "literal": "I + the grandchild of + Odongo.", 
            "english": "I'm the grandchild of Odongo"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Itiyo kanye?",
            "literal": "You work + where?", 
            "english": "Where do you work?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "Atiyo Safaricom.",
            "literal": "I work + Safaricom.", 
            "english": "I work for Safaricom."
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "In gi higni adi?",
            "literal": "You + with + years+ how many?", 
            "english": "How old are you?"
          },
          {
            "dholuo": "An gi higni apar gariyo.",
            "literal": "I + with + years + ten + plus two", 
            "english": "I am twelve years old."
          }
          
      ],
      "grammar_note": "Let's go over to the next section to see how these greetings play out in a conversation."
    }
  },

